defaultI am a solicitor with 16 year experience acting in Judicial Review Cases. Before becoming a Legal Aid Solicitor acting for Claimants, I acted a
defaults a Local Authority Solicitor. Please see below 
defaultan earlier document I prepared “Transforming Legal Aid Consultation: Response” upon which I also rely. I have also had sight of Dr Nick Armstrong’s submission (a barrister from Matrix Chambers) and would endo
defaultrse those detailed submissions wholeheartedly.
default&#xa0;
defaultI remain very concerned that the cuts to Legal Aid will mean cutting people off from justice. My main experience is in relation to judicial review and I note the judicial review legal aid proposal is that la
defaultwyers will not be paid unless the Court has granted permission to apply for judicial review. This proposal raises massive concerns for what legal scrutiny there will now be of state action. Many of the strongest cases never reach the permission stage of ju
defaultdicial review because Local Authorities settle. The way the proposal is now worded will force issuing of proceedings, when the reality is courts encourage parties to try and resolve matters if at all possible before issuing. 
default&#xa0;
defaultPlease see attached case stud
defaulty 3 in the 
defaultbelow
default paper: AES and Siblings. It will be noted that was an extremely strong case and a significant amount of work was carried out in preparing to issue proceedings. On the eve of proceedings being issued, the Local Authority finally conceded an
defaultd
default arranged suitable accommodation. This was an excellent result for the client. Unfortunately, 
defaultthe 
defaultnew proposals seem to be saying that in this type of case the Legal Aid Solicitor would be expected to do this work for nothing because proceedings have not 
defaultactually been issued. Clearly, solicitors who are already struggling are not going to be able to work for free and in this type of case the vulnerable will be left without assistance and Local Authorities will be able to 
defaultblatantly
default disregard their legal obl
defaultigations. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe MOJ now appears to be saying that if a case has been issued but settles without permission having been granted, there may be some discretion about paying the lawyers if there is a good reason why the Defendant has not been ordered to pay co
defaultsts. There are a large number of community care judicial review cases where the Claimant is entirely correct to issue proceedings based upon the facts at the time. However, if issuing proceedings focuses the Local Authority’s mind and leads to an assessmen
defaultt
default/service provision, by the time the case comes before the Judge, it is possible that permission may not be granted because the Local Authority has now done what is expected of them. In such cases, the Claimant will not automatically get costs and there on
defaultce again runs the risk of unpaid work despite an excellent result being achieved for the client. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAnother factor is to consider how many cases actually fall within the particular category of being issued and settling without permission having been granted
default. The reality is that many more cases are of the type described in the case study i.e. substantial work being carried out and the Defendant settling on the eve of issuing proceedings.
